<subsection xml:id="subsection-1-3-3">
    <title>Limits at Infinity and Dominance</title>
    <p>
        Let's consider <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{x}{e^x}</m>.  
        How might we go about finding this limit?  
        We cannot use the basic rules given above.  
        For these kinds of limits (often called "indeterminate"), it is handy to have some rules established in calculus.  
        They can easily be proved using L'Hopital's rule.  
    </p>

    <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-dominance">
        <title>Dominance Rules</title>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Exponential functions "dominate" polynomial functions.  
                        This means we have the following, where <m>>p(x)</m> is an <m>n</m>-degree polynomial and <m>a></m>$:
                        <md>
                             \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{p(x)}{a^x} = 0 \text{ and } \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{a^x}{p(x)} = \pm \infty.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Polynomial functions "dominate" logarithmic functions.  
                        This means we have the following, where <m>p(x)</m> is an <m>n</m>-degree polynomial and <m>\log(x)</m> is a generic logarithmic function:
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{p(x)}{\log(x)} = \pm \infty
                        </md>

                        and

                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{\log(x)}{p(x)} = \pm \infty.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Exponential functions ``dominate'' logarithmic functions.  
                        We get similar results as above.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Higher-degree polynomials "dominate" lower-degree polynomials.  
                        Let <m>p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m> be (non-constant) polynomial functions with <m>p(x)</m> with higher degree.  
                        We have the following:
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow \pm \infty} \frac{p(x)}{q(x)} = \pm \infty \text{ and } \lim_{x\rightarrow \pm \infty} \frac{q(x)}{p(x)} = 0.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        If <m>p(x)</m> and <m>q(x)</m> are polynomials with equal degree, with leading-term coefficients <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>>, respectively, then
                        <md>
                            \lim_{x\rightarrow \pm \infty} \frac{p(x)}{q(x)} = \pm \frac{a}{b}.
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>

        <p>
            Note that in the above, the whether the limits are positive or negative depend on whether the polynomial limits tend to <m>\infty</m> or <m>-\infty</m>.
        </p>
    </assemblage>

    <example xml:id="ex-dominance">
        <title>Dominance Rules</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the following limits:

                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} x^3 e^{-5x}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow -\infty} \frac{6-7x+5x^2}{8x^4+3x-\pi x + 1}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow 0} x^2 \ln(x)
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{4^x}{\ln(x-2)}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{5-x^2-4x^3}{9x^3 - 4x}
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        
        <answer>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\infty</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>-\frac{4}{9}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} x^3 e^{-5x} = \lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{x^3}{e^{5x}} = 0
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since the degree of the denominator is larger, the limit is <m>0</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Polynomials always dominate logarithms.  
                            So, this goes to <m>0</m> (because <m>x^2</m> tends to <m>0</m>).
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Exponentials always dominate logarithms.  
                            So this tends to <m>\infty</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The degrees of the polynomials are the same.  
                            So, <md>lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{5-x^2-4x^3}{9x^3 - 4x} = -\frac{4}{9}.</md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
</subsection>